<div id="review_392982279" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/392982279" />
    <a title="Matt" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4489591-matt"><img alt="Matt" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1309911900p2/4489591.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/392982279?book_show_action=true">Aug 16, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Matt" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Matt" href="/user/show/4489591-matt">Matt</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer392982279" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2999332621969421213">Well-researched, readable, with lots of pretty pictures if you&apos;re into that kind of thing. A couple of qualifications: <br/><br/>1. He is obviously most concerned with literary and fine arts, mostly ignoring decorative arts, architecture, performing arts, etc.<br/>2. He leans heavily on literary and artistic figures probably less well-known outside Eco&apos;s native Italy.<br/>3. His analysis tends to begin somewhat abstruse in the early chapters and really becomes engaging around the Renaissance and Enlightenment. (e.g</span>
  <span id="freeText2999332621969421213" style="display:none">Well-researched, readable, with lots of pretty pictures if you're into that kind of thing. A couple of qualifications: <br /><br />1. He is obviously most concerned with literary and fine arts, mostly ignoring decorative arts, architecture, performing arts, etc.<br />2. He leans heavily on literary and artistic figures probably less well-known outside Eco's native Italy.<br />3. His analysis tends to begin somewhat abstruse in the early chapters and really becomes engaging around the Renaissance and Enlightenment. (e.g. His observations about dandyism really connected a razor-sharp line from Oscar Wilde to handlebar-moustachioed hipsters, the self as raw material and artwork.)<br /><br />But as an introductory text demonstrating the visual arts over recorded history, it's an admirable survey with several excellent insights.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2999332621969421213" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


