<span id="freeTextContainer13841377265420520018">Reading Umberto Eco is always a bit of a task... his writing, his manner of explaining is one of a professor, not alway easy to comprehend but... he has a vision, he has (or I should say had, unfortunately) a clear view on (in this case) art and the beauty within... he takes us on journey through history via art and via the many way beauty was expressed... what is beautiful for one can be awful for another... <br/>this year I have read the biography of Leonardo Da Vinci and The Man in the Red Coat by</span>
  <span id="freeText13841377265420520018" style="display:none">Reading Umberto Eco is always a bit of a task... his writing, his manner of explaining is one of a professor, not alway easy to comprehend but... he has a vision, he has (or I should say had, unfortunately) a clear view on (in this case) art and the beauty within... he takes us on journey through history via art and via the many way beauty was expressed... what is beautiful for one can be awful for another... <br />this year I have read the biography of Leonardo Da Vinci and The Man in the Red Coat by Julian Barnes - this one was (kind of) connected to those books, simply because of the way Da Vinci left his mark on the arts and sciences and the late 19th, early 20th century that Barnes spoke of (with its dandyism and decadendism) were part of this essay as well!<br />I’ll be joining Eco again soon with his ‘On Ugliness’ and I’m looking forward to it!</span>
